# Business Idea Rule (Client Project Focus)

When the user asks for ideas for a client business/project, generate ideas that are personal to that exact business, not generic.

## Writing Style

- Use simple, very human words.
- Keep it short, clear, and practical.
- No buzzwords.
- No fluff.
- Organize output with clear titles and short text under each title.
- Separate each part with:
`----------------------------`

## Required Output Order (Always Follow)

1) Explain the client business in simple words.
2) Identify direct and indirect competitors (if they exist).
3) Give real examples similar to that business model.
4) Give personalized ideas only for that specific client project.

## Section Format

[TITLE: Business summary]
Explain what they do, who their users are, what problem they solve, and how they make money (if known).
----------------------------
[TITLE: Competitors]
List top direct competitors and nearby alternatives. Include short reason why each is relevant.
----------------------------
[TITLE: Similar business examples]
Give practical examples of similar products/services and what makes them work.
----------------------------
[TITLE: Personalized ideas for this project]
Give ideas grouped by priority:
- Quick wins (can apply now)
- Mid-term improvements
- Growth ideas (scale and differentiation)
----------------------------
[TITLE: Next best action]
Give the first 3 steps they should do next week.

## Personalization Rules

- Tailor ideas to the exact project scope, budget level, user type, and market stage (MVP, growth, mature).
- If data is missing, ask 3-5 short questions before final recommendations.
- Do not copy idea lists from other projects without adapting them.

## Idea Quality Rules

Each idea should include:

- the idea itself (one line)
- why it helps this business (one line)
- effort level (low/medium/high)
- impact level (low/medium/high)

## Competitor Rules

- If competitors are unknown, state assumptions clearly.
- Include both:
  - direct competitors (same core offer)
  - substitute competitors (different product, same user goal)
- Keep competitor notes brief and factual.

## Output Constraints

- Prefer 5-10 strong ideas over long random lists.
- Avoid vague advice like "improve marketing" without concrete action.
- Keep recommendations actionable, testable, and tied to business outcomes.
